<div id="review_3510330877" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3510330877" />
    <a title="Jin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/101938044-jin"><img alt="Jin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1591712713p2/101938044.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3510330877?book_show_action=true">Aug 23, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jin" href="/user/show/101938044-jin">Jin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3510330877" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer134420710416518753">I have mixed feelings with this one. I really love reading legal thrillers and I still regularly read them (John Grisham has been one of my favourite authors since ever). <br/><br/>Some parts of the book definitely deserves 5 stars! I really loved the back and forth between Zachary Blake and Kenny or Barrington and his &quot;entourage&quot;. I was also positively surprised by the epilogue because normally, they would just be boring, disclosing nothing new but this one wrapped up the story nicely. Furthermore, the b</span>
  <span id="freeText134420710416518753" style="display:none">I have mixed feelings with this one. I really love reading legal thrillers and I still regularly read them (John Grisham has been one of my favourite authors since ever). <br /><br />Some parts of the book definitely deserves 5 stars! I really loved the back and forth between Zachary Blake and Kenny or Barrington and his "entourage". I was also positively surprised by the epilogue because normally, they would just be boring, disclosing nothing new but this one wrapped up the story nicely. Furthermore, the book was not just a regular disturbed-teenagers-shooting-school-disaster but it shed light on this terrible incident from different aspects. I loved the involvement of high level institutions and other parts without being too exaggerating, and another plus point: it didn't have this typical overwhelming American heroism which I really liked.<br /><br />But I had a hard time to get into the story in the beginning. I couldn't connect to Kenny, Jake and their mother at all, their discussions and dialogues felt artificial and distant. The writing for Kenny got better in the end but I felt that he was still too cagey compared to the other characters in the story. Whenever Kenny and his friends were not in a chapter, I really liked the writing so much more and I kind of feel sorry for that. <br /><br />Betrayal High is definitely a good read for all fans of a good, fast-paced legal thriller. I really enjoyed reading this and I'm looking forward to the next Zachary Blake case!<br /><br />**I received a free copy of this book via Making Connections for leaving an honest review. The thoughts and opinions expressed are my own.**</span>
  <a data-text-id="134420710416518753" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


